```rust
struct User {
    id: i64,
    email: String,
    password_hash: String,
}

impl User {
    fn new(email: String, password: String) -> Self {
        let hash = bcrypt::hash(password, 12).unwrap();
        User { id: 0, email, password_hash: hash }
    }

    fn validate_password(&self, password: &str) -> bool {
        bcrypt::verify(password, &self.password_hash).unwrap()
    }

    fn send_welcome_email(&self) {
        let client = EmailClient::new("smtp.example.com");
        client.send(&self.email, "Welcome!", "Thanks for joining");
    }

    fn save_to_db(&self, conn: &Connection) -> Result<(), Error> {
        conn.execute("INSERT INTO users ...", &[&self.email])
    }
}
```

**SOLID violation: Single Responsibility Principle**

This User struct has too many responsibilities:
1. Password hashing/verification
2. Email sending
3. Database persistence

A struct should have ONE reason to change. This has 3.

**Refactored version:**

```rust
// User struct: Only data and domain logic
struct User {
    id: i64,
    email: String,
    password_hash: String,
}

// Password service: Handles hashing/verification
struct PasswordService;

impl PasswordService {
    fn hash_password(password: &str) -> Result<String, Error> {
        bcrypt::hash(password, 12)
            .map_err(|e| Error::HashError(e))
    }

    fn verify_password(password: &str, hash: &str) -> bool {
        bcrypt::verify(password, hash).unwrap_or(false)
    }
}

// Email service: Handles email sending
struct EmailService {
    client: EmailClient,
}

impl EmailService {
    fn send_welcome_email(&self, email: &str) {
        self.client.send(email, "Welcome!", "Thanks for joining");
    }
}

// Repository: Handles database operations
struct UserRepository<'a> {
    conn: &'a Connection,
}

impl<'a> UserRepository<'a> {
    fn save(&self, user: &User) -> Result<(), Error> {
        self.conn.execute(
            "INSERT INTO users (email, password_hash) VALUES (?, ?)",
            &[&user.email, &user.password_hash],
        )
    }
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- ✅ Each struct has ONE responsibility
- ✅ Easy to test in isolation
- ✅ Easy to swap implementations (mock email, different DB)
- ✅ Changes to email logic don't affect User
- ✅ Changes to password hashing don't affect User
- ✅ Follows separation of concerns

